window.GUIDE_TEXTS = {"patient":"Medication Counseling Guide for Hospital Pharmacy\n\nPurpose\n\nThis guide is for short, patient-friendly medication counseling in the hospital.\nIt is meant to help pharmacists and pharmacy interns explain new or changed\nmedications in plain language.\n\nUse this guide to explain:\n- What the medication is for\n- How it helps\n- The most useful side effects to know about\n- What symptoms should be reported right away\n- Simple safety reminders\n- Whether the medication may continue after discharge, if known\n\nThis guide does not replace pharmacist judgment, the medication order, the care\nteam plan, the hospital drug information system, or FDA-approved labeling.\n\nPharmacy interns may share verified information, but they should not answer\nclinical questions on their own. Questions that require judgment or a patient-\nspecific recommendation must be escalated to the supervising pharmacist.\n\n\nQuick Bedside Script\n\nOpening\n\n\"Hi, my name is _____. I am from the pharmacy team. I am here to talk with you\nabout new medications that were started in the hospital. Is now a good time?\"\n\nIf family, visitors, or caregivers are present:\n\n\"I see you have someone with you. Is it okay if we talk about your medications\nwhile they are here?\"\n\nPrivacy reminder:\n- Ask the patient\u0027s permission before discussing medications in front of family,\n  visitors, or caregivers.\n- If the patient wants privacy, pause until privacy is available.\n- If a caregiver is the correct person to teach, follow hospital policy.\n\n\nSimple Medication Counseling Template\n\nUse this for each medication.\n\nMedication name:\n______________________________________________\n\nWhy you are receiving it:\n\"You are receiving this medication for ______________________________.\"\n\nHow it helps:\n\"This medication helps by ______________________________.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n\"Some people may notice ______________________________. This is usually\nmanageable, but please tell your nurse or care team if it bothers you, gets\nworse, or makes you feel unsafe.\"\n[Source: ______________________________]\n\nHow often this happens:\n\"This is considered common / less common / rare but important. Exact chances\ndepend on the exact medication, dose, and your health situation.\"\n\nImportant warning sign:\n\"A less common but important warning sign is ______________________________.\nIf this happens, please tell your nurse or care team right away.\"\n[Source: ______________________________]\n\nMonitoring in the hospital:\n\"While you are here, the team may monitor ______________________________.\"\n\nDischarge or home-medication safety point, only if relevant:\n\"If this medication continues after discharge, the pharmacist or care team may\nreview medicines, over-the-counter products, vitamins, or supplements to avoid\nproblems.\"\n\nDischarge status, if known:\n\"Right now, this medication is expected to be continued / stopped / changed /\nstill being decided at discharge.\"\n\nPatient questions:\n\"What questions do you have?\"\n\nTeach-back:\n\"Just so I know I explained it clearly, can you tell me what this medication is\nfor, or what symptom you should report?\"\n\n\nWhat Pharmacy Interns Should Do\n\nInterns may:\n- Introduce themselves as part of the pharmacy team\n- Confirm whether now is a good time to talk\n- Ask permission before speaking in front of family or visitors\n- Share verified medication name, purpose, common side effects, warning signs,\n  and simple safety points\n- Use teach-back\n- Tell the patient they will review questions with the pharmacist\n\nInterns should escalate before answering questions about:\n- Why a medication was started if the reason is unclear\n- Whether a medication should be stopped, refused, restarted, or changed\n- Dose changes, lab results, kidney or liver function, drug levels, or discharge\n  plans\n- New symptoms that may be side effects\n- Allergic reaction, serious rash, swelling, trouble breathing, severe diarrhea,\n  bleeding, chest pain, fainting, confusion, seizure symptoms, or severe\n  dizziness\n- Drug interactions, duplicate therapy, pregnancy/lactation, transplant\n  medication levels, anticoagulation, insulin changes, opioid safety, or taper\n  plans\n\nSuggested intern wording:\n\n\"That is an important question. I want to make sure you get the correct answer,\nso I am going to review it with the pharmacist.\"\n\n\nPatient-friendly wording:\n\n\"Most people tolerate this medication. Some people may notice _____. Please tell\nyour nurse if it is bothering you or getting worse.\"\n\n\"A less common but more important symptom is _____. If that happens, tell your\nnurse or care team right away.\"\n\nSimple side-effect meaning:\n- Common: happens often enough that it is useful to mention; usually manageable\n- Less common: not expected for most people, but possible\n- Rare but serious: not likely, but important to report right away\n- Important: may need monitoring, treatment, or a dose change\n- Urgent warning sign: tell the nurse or care team right away\n\nFrequency wording for patient counseling:\n- Very common: about 10% or more of patients\n- Common: about 1% to less than 10% of patients\n- Less common: less than 1% of patients, or not expected for most people\n- Rare but serious: uncommon, but important because it may need urgent review\n- Varies: the chance changes a lot by medication, dose, reason for use, kidney\n  or liver function, length of therapy, and other patient factors\n\nFor broad medication groups, use frequency words instead of exact percentages\nunless the exact medication and source are known. For exact numbers, verify with\nDailyMed, the package insert, Lexicomp, Micromedex, or the hospital-approved\ndrug reference.\n\n\nMedication Interaction Safety Checks\n\nIn the hospital, medication interactions are primarily the responsibility of the\npharmacist, provider, and care team. Patients usually do not control which\nmedications are administered while they are admitted.\n\nDo not routinely counsel patients on inpatient drug-drug interactions.\n\nInstead:\n- The pharmacist or intern should screen for interactions before counseling.\n- If an interaction concern is found, escalate it to the supervising pharmacist\n  or care team.\n- Discuss interactions with the patient only if they affect something the\n  patient controls, such as home medications, over-the-counter products,\n  vitamins, supplements, alcohol use, herbal products, or discharge medications.\n\nPatient-friendly wording, only when relevant:\n\n\"While you are in the hospital, the care team checks your medications for\ninteractions. If this medication continues after discharge, pharmacy can review\nwhat to avoid at home.\"\n\n\"Before taking new over-the-counter medicines, vitamins, supplements, or herbal\nproducts after discharge, please check with your pharmacist or care team.\"\n\n\nCommon Medication Groups\n\nUse these as quick patient-friendly prompts. Always confirm the patient-specific\nreason before counseling.\n\nEach medication group includes:\n- Common side effects: symptoms that happen often enough to mention briefly.\n- Less common or rare warning signs: symptoms that are not expected for most\n  patients but should be reported right away because they may need prompt review.\n\nThese sections are a counseling overview, not a full adverse-effect list. For a\nspecific medication, verify exact frequency and warning details with DailyMed,\nthe package insert, Lexicomp, Micromedex, or the hospital-approved drug\nreference.\n\n\n1. Antibiotics\n\nExamples:\nAzithromycin, cefazolin, cefepime, ceftriaxone, doxycycline, ertapenem,\npiperacillin-tazobactam, vancomycin, linezolid, metronidazole, levofloxacin,\nciprofloxacin.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This antibiotic is being used to treat or prevent an infection. The plan may\nchange when the team gets more test or culture results.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Nausea, loose stools, mild diarrhea, headache, or rash may happen. These are\n  generally common, but the chance varies by antibiotic and length of treatment.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label; CDC antibiotic side effects]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe, watery, bloody, or persistent diarrhea. This is less common but\n  important. [Source: CDC C. diff]\n- Trouble breathing, swelling, hives, or a severe rash. This is rare but\n  serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- New confusion, seizure-like symptoms, severe dizziness, or unusual weakness\n  with certain antibiotics. This is less common but important. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n- New muscle pain or weakness with daptomycin. This is less common but\n  important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Tendon pain, numbness/tingling, mood changes, or severe blood sugar changes\n  with fluoroquinolones such as levofloxacin or ciprofloxacin. These are less\n  common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for interactions with vitamins/minerals, anticoagulants, seizure\nmedicines, heart-rhythm medicines, or transplant medicines. Discuss with the\npatient only if it affects discharge or home-medication use.\n\n\n2. Blood Thinners and Antiplatelets\n\nExamples:\nHeparin, enoxaparin, apixaban, rivaroxaban, warfarin, aspirin, clopidogrel,\nticagrelor.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication lowers the chance of harmful blood clots or helps prevent\nplatelets from sticking together. Because it affects bleeding or clotting,\nbleeding is the main safety point.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Bruising or minor bleeding can happen. This is common enough to mention with\n  blood thinners.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Vomit that looks like blood or coffee grounds. This is less common but\n  serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Black or bloody stool. This is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Blood in urine. This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Severe headache, new weakness, confusion, fall, or head injury. This is less\n  common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Bleeding that will not stop. This is less common but serious. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for duplicate anticoagulants/antiplatelets, NSAIDs, procedures, renal\nfunction, and bleeding risk. Discuss OTC pain relievers only if relevant to\ndischarge or home use.\n\n\n3. Diabetes Medications\n\nExamples:\nInsulin glargine, rapid-acting insulin such as insulin lispro, metformin,\nempagliflozin, dapagliflozin.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps manage blood sugar. In the hospital, blood sugar can\nchange because of illness, meals, tube feeds, steroids, surgery, or kidney\nfunction.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Insulin can cause low blood sugar. This is common and clinically important.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label; MedlinePlus hypoglycemia]\n- Metformin can cause stomach upset or diarrhea. This is common, especially\n  when starting or increasing the dose. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- SGLT2 medicines such as empagliflozin or dapagliflozin can increase urination\n  or genital/urinary infection risk. These are common enough to mention.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Shaking, sweating, confusion, weakness, fast heartbeat, or feeling like blood\n  sugar is low. Low blood sugar is common with insulin and should be reported\n  early. [Source: MedlinePlus hypoglycemia]\n- Vomiting, severe weakness, fast breathing, or feeling very ill with diabetes\n  medicines. This is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Pain, redness, swelling, fever, or serious infection symptoms in the genital\n  area with SGLT2 medicines. This is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n\nPatient-controlled safety point:\n\"Please tell staff if you miss a meal, cannot eat, vomit, or feel symptoms of\nlow blood sugar.\"\n\n\n4. Heart Failure, Blood Pressure, and Diuretics\n\nExamples:\nSacubitril-valsartan, lisinopril, losartan, carvedilol, metoprolol, furosemide,\nbumetanide, torsemide, spironolactone, nitroglycerin.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps with blood pressure, heart rate, fluid, or heart\nprotection.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Dizziness, tiredness, increased urination, or lower blood pressure can happen.\n  These are common enough to mention, especially when doses are started or\n  changed. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Fainting, severe dizziness, chest pain, or trouble breathing. This is less\n  common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Very slow heart rate or feeling like you may pass out with beta-blockers.\n  This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Muscle weakness, severe cramps, or heart-rhythm symptoms that may suggest\n  electrolyte changes. This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Swelling of the face, lips, tongue, or throat with ACE inhibitors such as\n  lisinopril. This is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for potassium, kidney function, duplicate blood pressure therapy, and\nmedicines that may increase dizziness or low blood pressure. Routine patient\ncounseling should focus on symptoms to report.\n\n\n5. Breathing Medicines\n\nExamples:\nAlbuterol, ipratropium-albuterol, tiotropium, fluticasone-salmeterol,\nbudesonide-formoterol.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps your breathing. Some inhalers or breathing treatments\nwork quickly, and others are maintenance medicines.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Shakiness or fast heartbeat can be common with rescue breathing medicines such\n  as albuterol. Dry mouth, hoarseness, or throat irritation can also happen and\n  frequency varies by inhaler. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Chest pain, severe fast heartbeat, or feeling faint. This is less common but\n  important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Breathing that gets worse right after a treatment. This is rare but serious.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Fever, worsening cough, or symptoms of pneumonia with inhaled steroid\n  combinations. This is less common but important, especially in COPD. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMedication history point:\n\"If you use inhalers at home, tell the team which ones you use.\"\n\nPractical tip:\n\"If this inhaler contains a steroid and you continue it after discharge, rinse\nyour mouth after using it to lower the chance of thrush.\" [Source: DailyMed FDA\nlabel]\n\n\n6. Transplant and Immune-System Medicines\n\nExamples:\nTacrolimus, cyclosporine, mycophenolate, sirolimus, everolimus, belatacept,\nantithymocyte globulin.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication lowers immune activity to help protect your transplant or treat\nan immune-related problem.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Tremor, headache, diarrhea, nausea, infection risk, blood pressure changes,\n  kidney lab changes, or blood count changes may happen. These are common to\n  very common for some transplant medicines, but the exact chance varies by\n  medicine and transplant regimen. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Fever, chills, sore throat, or other infection symptoms. Infection risk is\n  common and can become serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Severe diarrhea, vomiting, or inability to keep medicines down. This is less\n  common but important because missed doses can matter. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Severe tremor, confusion, seizure symptoms, or major change in alertness.\n  This is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Very low urine output, major swelling, or concern for kidney problems. This is\n  less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nTransplant medicines have many clinically important interactions. Screen with\nthe pharmacist/transplant team. Discuss with the patient only for discharge,\nhome medicines, supplements, herbal products, or missed-dose instructions.\n\n\n7. Infection-Prevention Medicines for Transplant or Low Immunity\n\nExamples:\nValganciclovir, ganciclovir, sulfamethoxazole-trimethoprim, atovaquone,\ndapsone, pentamidine, fluconazole, voriconazole, posaconazole.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps prevent or treat infections while your immune system is\nweaker.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Nausea, diarrhea, headache, and rash are common enough to mention for many of\n  these medicines. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Blood count changes, kidney/liver lab changes, or electrolyte changes vary by\n  medicine and are often found by monitoring labs. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Fever, chills, sore throat, unusual bruising, or signs of low blood counts.\n  This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Severe rash or trouble breathing. This is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed\n  FDA label]\n- Yellow skin/eyes, dark urine, severe stomach pain, or concern for liver\n  problems. This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Severe weakness, shortness of breath, blue/gray lips, or dark urine with\n  dapsone. This is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen antifungals and antivirals for interactions with transplant medicines,\nanticoagulants, statins, seizure medicines, and heart-rhythm medicines. Discuss\nwith the patient only if relevant to discharge or home use.\n\n\n8. Pain Medicines: Non-Opioid\n\nExamples:\nAcetaminophen, ibuprofen, ketorolac, naproxen, lidocaine patches.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps with pain or fever.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Acetaminophen is usually well tolerated at safe doses; side effects are\n  uncommon when total daily dose is safe. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- NSAIDs such as ibuprofen, ketorolac, and naproxen can irritate the stomach and\n  affect bleeding risk, blood pressure, or kidneys. These risks vary by dose,\n  length of use, kidney function, bleeding risk, and other conditions. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe stomach pain, black/bloody stool, vomiting blood, or unusual bleeding\n  with NSAIDs. This is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Yellow skin/eyes, dark urine, or severe nausea after too much acetaminophen.\n  This is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen NSAIDs and acetaminophen for bleeding, kidney, liver, heart failure, and\nduplicate-therapy risks. Discuss OTC pain medicine only if discharge or home use\nis relevant.\n\n\n9. Pain Medicines: Opioids\n\nExamples:\nOxycodone, hydromorphone, morphine, fentanyl, hydrocodone-acetaminophen.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication treats moderate to severe pain. In the hospital, nurses give\nit based on the care team\u0027s orders and safety checks.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Sleepiness, constipation, nausea, and dizziness are common with opioids. Fall\n  risk is clinically important, especially in the hospital. [Source: FDA opioid\n  safety communication; DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Very slow or difficult breathing. This is less common but serious. [Source:\n  FDA opioid safety communication]\n- Extreme sleepiness, confusion, or hard to wake up. This is less common but\n  serious. [Source: FDA opioid safety communication]\n- Severe dizziness or a fall. This is less common but important. [Source: FDA\n  opioid safety communication]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for benzodiazepines, gabapentin/pregabalin, sleep medicines, alcohol use,\nand other sedating medicines. For inpatient counseling, focus on reporting\nexcessive sleepiness or breathing problems.\n\n\n10. Steroids\n\nExamples:\nPrednisone, methylprednisolone, dexamethasone, hydrocortisone.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"Steroids reduce inflammation or help with conditions such as breathing\nproblems, allergic reactions, autoimmune conditions, or adrenal problems.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Increased appetite, trouble sleeping, mood changes, fluid retention, and\n  higher blood sugar are common enough to mention, especially with higher doses\n  or longer courses. [Source: DailyMed FDA label; MedlinePlus prednisone]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe mood changes, confusion, signs of infection, black/bloody stool, or\n  very high blood sugar symptoms. These are less common but important. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label; MedlinePlus prednisone]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for diabetes therapy changes, NSAIDs, anticoagulants/antiplatelets, and\ninfection risk. Discuss discharge taper or home OTC use only if relevant.\n\n\n11. Nausea Medicines\n\nExamples:\nOndansetron, prochlorperazine, promethazine, metoclopramide.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps prevent or treat nausea and vomiting.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Sleepiness, dizziness, constipation, or headache may happen. These are common\n  enough to mention, but the chance varies by nausea medicine. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Fainting, racing heartbeat, severe dizziness, or heart-rhythm symptoms. This\n  is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Restlessness, tremor, stiffness, or unusual movements with metoclopramide or\n  similar medicines. This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for sedation, QT prolongation, dopamine-blocking combinations, and\nserotonergic combinations. Patient counseling should focus on symptoms to report.\n\n\n12. Bowel Medicines\n\nExamples:\nSenna, polyethylene glycol, docusate, bisacodyl, lactulose.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps with constipation or helps meet bowel movement goals.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Cramping, gas, loose stools, or diarrhea are common enough to mention with\n  bowel medicines. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe diarrhea, severe stomach pain, dehydration symptoms, or no bowel\n  movement when the care team expected one. This is less common but important.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPatient-controlled safety point:\n\"Please tell staff about diarrhea, constipation, or missed bowel movements so\nthe plan can be adjusted.\"\n\n\n13. Psychiatric, Sleep, and Anxiety Medicines\n\nExamples:\nSertraline, escitalopram, quetiapine, haloperidol, trazodone, melatonin,\nlorazepam.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication may help with mood, anxiety, sleep, agitation, delirium, or\nanother mental health or neurologic symptom.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Sleepiness, dizziness, dry mouth, or nausea are common enough to mention for\n  many of these medicines. Fall risk is clinically important in the hospital.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe sleepiness, confusion, slowed breathing, or falls with sedating\n  medicines. This is less common but serious. [Source: FDA opioid/benzodiazepine\n  safety communication; DailyMed FDA label]\n- New suicidal thoughts, severe mood changes, severe restlessness, stiffness, or\n  abnormal movements. These are less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for opioids, benzodiazepines, sleep medicines, alcohol use, QT-risk\nmedicines, serotonergic combinations, and duplicate sedating therapy. Patient\ncounseling should focus on sedation, falls, breathing, and behavior changes.\n\n\n14. Seizure Medicines\n\nExamples:\nLevetiracetam, phenytoin, valproate, lacosamide, carbamazepine, oxcarbazepine,\nlamotrigine, topiramate, phenobarbital, gabapentin.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication helps prevent or treat seizures, or it may be used for another\ncondition such as nerve pain, mood, migraine prevention, or withdrawal. We\nconfirm the reason from your chart.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Sleepiness, dizziness, trouble walking, nausea, headache, or mood changes may\n  happen depending on the medication. Many seizure medicines commonly cause\n  sleepiness or dizziness, especially when starting or changing doses. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe rash, blistering rash, mouth sores, or skin peeling with medicines such\n  as lamotrigine or carbamazepine. This is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed\n  FDA label]\n- Severe confusion, unsteady walking, slurred speech, abnormal eye movements, or\n  extreme sleepiness. This is less common but important and may suggest too much\n  medication effect. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- New or worsening depression, suicidal thoughts, or major behavior changes.\n  This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Severe stomach pain, yellow skin/eyes, or unusual bleeding/bruising with\n  valproate. This is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Slowed breathing when gabapentin or phenobarbital is combined with opioids,\n  benzodiazepines, alcohol, or other sedating medicines. This is less common but\n  serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label; FDA opioid/CNS depressant safety\n  communication; FDA gabapentin/pregabalin safety communication]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen seizure medicines for interactions, duplicate therapy, levels, renal or\nhepatic dosing, and discharge medication changes. Discuss with the patient only\nif relevant to discharge or home medication use.\n\n\n15. Electrolytes and Supplements\n\nExamples:\nPotassium, magnesium, phosphate, iron, vitamin D, thiamine, folic acid.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This replaces or supports something your body needs.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Iron can cause constipation or dark stool. This is common enough to mention.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Magnesium can cause diarrhea. This is common enough to mention. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n- Potassium can irritate the stomach. This is common enough to mention,\n  especially with oral tablets or liquid. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Severe stomach pain, severe diarrhea, vomiting, chest symptoms, severe\n  weakness, or trouble swallowing tablets. This is less common but important.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen supplements for absorption issues with antibiotics, thyroid medicine, and\nother oral therapies. Discuss timing with the patient only if the medication\nwill continue after discharge.\n\n\n16. Alcohol Withdrawal or Substance-Use Medicines\n\nExamples:\nLorazepam, diazepam, phenobarbital, thiamine, folic acid, multivitamin,\nbuprenorphine, methadone, naltrexone.\n\nSimple purpose:\n\"This medication may help treat withdrawal, prevent vitamin problems, reduce\ncravings, or support treatment for opioid use disorder.\"\n\nCommon side effects:\n- Sleepiness, dizziness, nausea, constipation, or sweating may happen depending\n  on the medication. Sleepiness and dizziness are common enough to mention with\n  sedating withdrawal medicines and opioid-use-disorder medicines. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nTell the nurse or care team right away for:\n- Very slow breathing, extreme sleepiness, confusion, fainting, or severe\n  dizziness. This is less common but serious. [Source: FDA opioid/benzodiazepine\n  safety communication; DailyMed FDA label]\n- Chest palpitations or fainting with methadone. This is less common but\n  important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMedication history point:\n\"Please tell the team about anything you take at home or outside the hospital.\"\n\nPharmacy safety check, not routine patient counseling:\nScreen for opioids, benzodiazepines, phenobarbital, alcohol use, sleep\nmedicines, QT-risk medicines, and other sedating medicines.\n\n\nDocumentation Prompts\n\nDocument per hospital workflow:\n- Medication name\n- Verified indication\n- Main counseling points covered\n- Important warning sign reviewed, if applicable\n- Safety point reviewed, if applicable\n- Interaction concern escalated or pharmacist-reviewed, if applicable\n- Patient/caregiver understanding using teach-back\n- Questions escalated to pharmacist or care team\n\n\nSource Notes\n\nUse hospital-approved references for final verification. Frequency and warning\nsign wording in this guide is intentionally simplified for patient counseling.\nExact percentages should be verified for the exact medication, dose, indication,\nand patient population.\n\n- DailyMed Drug Labels\n  https://dailymed.nlm.nih.gov/dailymed/\n  Use for FDA-approved medication labels, adverse reaction frequency tables,\n  boxed warnings, warnings/precautions, contraindications, and interaction\n  information.\n\n- CDC: Antibiotic Use and Side Effects\n  https://www.cdc.gov/antibiotic-use/\n  Use for patient-friendly antibiotic side-effect counseling.\n\n- CDC: C. diff\n  https://www.cdc.gov/c-diff/\n  Use for antibiotic-associated severe diarrhea and C. diff counseling.\n\n- FDA: Opioid Pain Medicines Safety Information\n  https://www.fda.gov/drugs/information-drug-class/opioid-medications\n  Use for opioid safety, overdose, slowed breathing, dependence, and safe-use\n  counseling.\n\n- FDA: Opioids with Benzodiazepines or Other CNS Depressants\n  https://www.fda.gov/drugs/drug-safety-and-availability/fda-drug-safety-communication-fda-warns-about-serious-risks-and-death-when-combining-opioid\n  Use for serious sedation and breathing-risk counseling when opioids are\n  combined with benzodiazepines, alcohol, sleep medicines, or other CNS\n  depressants.\n\n- FDA: Gabapentin/Pregabalin and Serious Breathing Problems\n  https://www.fda.gov/drugs/drug-safety-and-availability/fda-warns-about-serious-breathing-problems-seizure-and-nerve-pain-medicines-gabapentin\n  Use for breathing-risk counseling when gabapentin or pregabalin is combined\n  with opioids or other CNS depressants, or when patients have respiratory risk\n  factors.\n\n- MedlinePlus: Hypoglycemia\n  https://medlineplus.gov/hypoglycemia.html\n  Use for patient-friendly low blood sugar symptoms.\n\n- MedlinePlus: Prednisone\n  https://medlineplus.gov/druginfo/meds/a601102.html\n  Use for patient-friendly steroid counseling.\n","detailed":"Medication Side Effect Detailed Reference for Pharmacy Review\n\nPurpose\n\nThis companion file is for pharmacist and pharmacy intern preparation. It gives\nmore detailed side-effect information than the patient-facing counseling guide.\nDo not read this file word-for-word to patients.\n\nUse this file to:\n- Choose the most relevant patient counseling points.\n- Distinguish common side effects from less common but important warning signs.\n- Identify which side effects need pharmacist review, monitoring, or escalation.\n- Keep source tags next to the side-effect information.\n\nFor patient counseling, use medication_counseling_guide.txt.\n\n\nFrequency Language\n\n- Very common: about 10% or more.\n- Common: about 1% to less than 10%.\n- Less common: less than 1%, or not expected for most patients.\n- Rare but serious: uncommon, but important because delayed recognition may\n  cause harm.\n- Varies: frequency depends heavily on exact medication, dose, route, duration,\n  indication, kidney/liver function, age, comorbidities, and interacting drugs.\n\nFor exact medication-specific percentages, verify with DailyMed, the package\ninsert, Lexicomp, Micromedex, or the hospital-approved drug information\nresource.\n\n\n1. Antibiotics\n\nExamples:\nAzithromycin, cefazolin, cefepime, ceftriaxone, doxycycline, ertapenem,\npiperacillin-tazobactam, vancomycin, linezolid, metronidazole, levofloxacin,\nciprofloxacin, daptomycin, gentamicin, tobramycin.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Nausea, loose stools, mild diarrhea, abdominal discomfort, headache, and mild\n  rash are common enough to mention for many antibiotics, but rates vary widely\n  by antibiotic and regimen. [Source: DailyMed FDA label; CDC antibiotic side\n  effects]\n- Infusion-site discomfort, redness, or itching may occur with IV antibiotics;\n  frequency varies by agent and infusion method. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Severe, watery, bloody, or persistent diarrhea may suggest C. diff or another\n  clinically significant diarrhea syndrome. It is less common than mild loose\n  stools but important to report early. [Source: CDC C. diff; DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Trouble breathing, swelling, hives, or severe rash may suggest serious\n  allergy. This is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- New confusion, seizure-like symptoms, severe dizziness, or unusual weakness\n  can occur with selected antibiotics, especially with renal impairment or high\n  exposure. This is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Daptomycin: muscle pain or weakness with CPK elevation is less common but\n  important; eosinophilic pneumonia is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Fluoroquinolones: tendon pain/rupture, neuropathy, CNS effects, QT-related\n  symptoms, severe blood sugar changes, and aortic aneurysm/dissection risk in\n  selected patients are less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Aminoglycosides: kidney injury, hearing changes, ringing in the ears, balance\n  problems, and neuromuscular weakness are less common but important and often\n  exposure-related. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Linezolid: thrombocytopenia, anemia, serotonin syndrome, lactic acidosis,\n  neuropathy, and very low blood sugar are less common but important. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review allergies, renal function, culture data, duration, IV-to-oral plan,\n  duplicate therapy, and drug levels when applicable.\n- Escalate severe rash, breathing symptoms, severe diarrhea, mental status\n  changes, seizure symptoms, or suspected toxicity.\n\n\n2. Blood Thinners and Antiplatelets\n\nExamples:\nHeparin, enoxaparin, apixaban, rivaroxaban, warfarin, aspirin, clopidogrel,\nticagrelor.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Bruising, minor bleeding, nosebleeds, or injection-site bruising can happen\n  and are common enough to mention with anticoagulants or antiplatelets.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Mild injection-site pain or bruising can occur with injectable agents such as\n  heparin or enoxaparin. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Vomiting blood or material that looks like coffee grounds is less common but\n  serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Black or bloody stool is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Blood in urine is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Severe headache, new weakness, confusion, fall, or head injury may indicate\n  serious bleeding risk and should be escalated. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Bleeding that does not stop is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Heparin-induced thrombocytopenia is uncommon but important because it can\n  increase clotting risk despite low platelets. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Warfarin skin necrosis and purple toe syndrome are rare but serious. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review hemoglobin/hematocrit, platelets, renal function, INR for warfarin,\n  procedure timing, neuraxial precautions, duplicate anticoagulation, and bleed\n  history.\n- Escalate any suspected major bleed, head injury, rapid hemoglobin drop, or HIT\n  concern.\n\n\n3. Diabetes Medications\n\nExamples:\nInsulin glargine, rapid-acting insulin such as insulin lispro, metformin,\nempagliflozin, dapagliflozin.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Insulin: hypoglycemia is common and clinically important; frequency varies by\n  regimen, nutrition status, renal function, glucose targets, and illness.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label; MedlinePlus hypoglycemia]\n- Insulin: injection-site reactions can occur; frequency varies by product and\n  route. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Metformin: nausea, diarrhea, abdominal discomfort, and metallic taste are\n  common, especially when starting or increasing dose. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- SGLT2 inhibitors: increased urination and genital mycotic infections are\n  common enough to mention; UTI risk may occur. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Insulin: confusion, seizure, inability to swallow, or severe low blood sugar\n  symptoms are serious and require prompt treatment. [Source: MedlinePlus\n  hypoglycemia; DailyMed FDA label]\n- Metformin: lactic acidosis is rare but serious, especially with renal\n  dysfunction, hypoxia, severe illness, or excess alcohol use. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n- SGLT2 inhibitors: euglycemic ketoacidosis, serious UTI/urosepsis, Fournier\n  gangrene, and marked dehydration are rare or less common but serious. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review nutrition status, missed meals, tube feeds, steroid changes, renal\n  function, perioperative status, and acute illness.\n- Escalate severe hypoglycemia symptoms, DKA symptoms, dehydration, genital\n  infection concerns, or lactic acidosis concern.\n\n\n4. Heart Failure, Blood Pressure, and Diuretics\n\nExamples:\nSacubitril-valsartan, lisinopril, losartan, carvedilol, metoprolol, furosemide,\nbumetanide, torsemide, spironolactone, nitroglycerin.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Dizziness, fatigue, lower blood pressure, and lightheadedness are common\n  enough to mention, especially when starting or changing therapy. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n- Loop diuretics: increased urination is expected; dizziness, dehydration,\n  kidney function changes, and electrolyte changes can occur. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n- Beta-blockers: fatigue, dizziness, lower heart rate, and lower blood pressure\n  are common enough to mention. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Spironolactone: breast tenderness/gynecomastia and hyperkalemia risk may\n  occur; frequency varies by population and dose. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Fainting, severe dizziness, chest pain, or trouble breathing are less common\n  but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Very slow heart rate or feeling like the patient may pass out with beta-\n  blockers is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Muscle weakness, severe cramps, or heart-rhythm symptoms may suggest\n  electrolyte problems and are less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- ACE inhibitors: swelling of the face, lips, tongue, or throat is rare but\n  serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Nitroglycerin or other vasodilators: severe hypotension or syncope is less\n  common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review blood pressure, heart rate, renal function, potassium, magnesium,\n  volume status, fall risk, and duplicate therapy.\n- Escalate syncope, severe hypotension, angioedema symptoms, severe electrolyte\n  symptoms, or acute kidney injury concern.\n\n\n5. Breathing Medicines\n\nExamples:\nAlbuterol, ipratropium-albuterol, tiotropium, fluticasone-salmeterol,\nbudesonide-formoterol.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Albuterol: shakiness, nervousness, fast heartbeat, headache, and dizziness are\n  common enough to mention. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Anticholinergic inhalers: dry mouth, throat irritation, constipation, or\n  urinary symptoms may occur; frequency varies by product. [Source: DailyMed\n  FDA label]\n- Inhaled steroids: hoarseness, throat irritation, and oral thrush can occur;\n  rinsing the mouth lowers thrush risk. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Chest pain, severe fast heartbeat, or feeling faint is less common but\n  important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Paradoxical bronchospasm, meaning breathing gets worse right after treatment,\n  is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Pneumonia risk with inhaled steroid combinations is less common but important,\n  especially in COPD. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Eye pain/blurred vision from nebulized anticholinergic exposure is less common\n  but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review rescue vs maintenance inhaler use, duplicate inhalers, inhaler\n  technique if discharge use is planned, and symptoms after treatment.\n- Escalate paradoxical bronchospasm, severe tachycardia, chest pain, or\n  pneumonia concern.\n\n\n6. Transplant and Immune-System Medicines\n\nExamples:\nTacrolimus, cyclosporine, mycophenolate, sirolimus, everolimus, belatacept,\nantithymocyte globulin.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Tacrolimus/cyclosporine: tremor, headache, blood pressure changes, kidney lab\n  changes, potassium/magnesium changes, glucose changes, and infection risk are\n  common to very common in some transplant populations. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Mycophenolate: diarrhea, nausea/vomiting, leukopenia, anemia, infection risk,\n  and GI symptoms are common enough to mention. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Sirolimus/everolimus: edema, mouth sores, lipid changes, cytopenias, wound\n  healing concerns, and infection risk may occur; frequency varies by regimen.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Antithymocyte globulin: fever, chills, infusion reactions, low white blood\n  cells, low platelets, and infection risk may occur. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Fever, chills, sore throat, or other infection symptoms are important because\n  infection risk is clinically significant. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Severe diarrhea, vomiting, or inability to keep medicines down is important\n  because missed doses or altered levels can matter. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Severe tremor, confusion, seizure symptoms, or major alertness changes may\n  suggest neurotoxicity or high levels and are less common but serious. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n- Very low urine output, major swelling, or kidney problem concern is less\n  common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Serious infusion reaction, anaphylaxis, serum sickness, severe cytopenias, or\n  cardiopulmonary symptoms with antithymocyte globulin are less common but\n  serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review transplant organ, regimen, drug levels, renal function, liver function,\n  CBC, electrolytes, infection symptoms, and adherence/missed doses.\n- Escalate suspected infection, severe cytopenias, high/low drug levels,\n  nephrotoxicity, neurotoxicity, or infusion reaction.\n\n\n7. Infection-Prevention Medicines for Transplant or Low Immunity\n\nExamples:\nValganciclovir, ganciclovir, sulfamethoxazole-trimethoprim, atovaquone,\ndapsone, pentamidine, fluconazole, voriconazole, posaconazole.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Nausea, diarrhea, headache, and rash are common enough to mention for many of\n  these medicines. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Blood count changes, kidney/liver lab changes, and electrolyte changes vary\n  by medicine and are often detected by lab monitoring. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Voriconazole: visual changes are common enough to mention and may be\n  transient. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Posaconazole and other azoles: GI symptoms, liver enzyme changes, and\n  electrolyte abnormalities may occur. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Fever, chills, sore throat, unusual bruising, or signs of low blood counts are\n  less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Severe rash or trouble breathing is rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Yellow skin/eyes, dark urine, or severe stomach pain may suggest liver injury\n  and is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Dapsone: severe weakness, shortness of breath, blue/gray lips, dark urine,\n  hemolysis, or methemoglobinemia symptoms are less common but serious. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n- Pentamidine: breathing difficulty, blood pressure changes, kidney injury,\n  pancreatitis symptoms, arrhythmia risk, blood sugar changes, or severe\n  electrolyte abnormalities are less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review renal dosing, CBC, liver function, electrolytes, glucose, QT risk, and\n  transplant medication levels when applicable.\n- Escalate severe rash, cytopenia concern, liver injury concern, respiratory\n  symptoms, hemolysis/methemoglobinemia concern, or QT/arrhythmia symptoms.\n\n\n8. Pain Medicines: Non-Opioid\n\nExamples:\nAcetaminophen, ibuprofen, ketorolac, naproxen, lidocaine patches.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Acetaminophen is usually well tolerated at safe doses; side effects are\n  uncommon when the total daily dose is safe. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- NSAIDs can cause stomach irritation, nausea, dyspepsia, edema, higher blood\n  pressure, kidney effects, and bleeding risk; frequency varies by dose,\n  duration, and patient risk factors. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Lidocaine patches may cause local skin redness, irritation, or discomfort.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- NSAIDs: severe stomach pain, black/bloody stool, vomiting blood, unusual\n  bleeding, kidney injury, fluid retention, or serious cardiovascular events are\n  less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Acetaminophen: yellow skin/eyes, dark urine, severe nausea, or liver injury\n  symptoms after excess exposure are rare but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Lidocaine: systemic toxicity is rare with correct patch use but serious if it\n  occurs. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review total acetaminophen dose, liver risk, kidney function, bleeding risk,\n  anticoagulants/antiplatelets, heart failure, and GI bleed history.\n- Escalate suspected GI bleed, liver injury, kidney injury, or excess\n  acetaminophen exposure.\n\n\n9. Pain Medicines: Opioids\n\nExamples:\nOxycodone, hydromorphone, morphine, fentanyl, hydrocodone-acetaminophen.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Sleepiness, constipation, nausea, dizziness, itching, and fall risk are common\n  enough to mention. [Source: DailyMed FDA label; FDA opioid safety\n  communication]\n- Constipation is common and often needs a bowel regimen when opioids continue.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Very slow or difficult breathing is less common but serious. [Source: FDA\n  opioid safety communication]\n- Extreme sleepiness, confusion, or being hard to wake is less common but\n  serious. [Source: FDA opioid safety communication]\n- Severe dizziness or a fall is less common but important. [Source: FDA opioid\n  safety communication]\n- Serotonin syndrome may occur with selected opioids and serotonergic medicines;\n  this is less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review pain control, sedation, respiratory status, bowel regimen, fall risk,\n  renal function, opioid tolerance, duplicate sedatives, and naloxone if\n  discharge opioids are planned.\n- Escalate respiratory depression, oversedation, delirium, fall, or suspected\n  overdose.\n\n\n10. Steroids\n\nExamples:\nPrednisone, methylprednisolone, dexamethasone, hydrocortisone.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Increased appetite, trouble sleeping, mood changes, fluid retention, and\n  higher blood sugar are common enough to mention, especially with higher doses\n  or longer courses. [Source: DailyMed FDA label; MedlinePlus prednisone]\n- GI upset, blood pressure changes, and infection risk may occur; frequency\n  varies by dose and duration. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Severe mood changes, confusion, psychosis, signs of infection, black/bloody\n  stool, or very high blood sugar symptoms are less common but important.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label; MedlinePlus prednisone]\n- Adrenal suppression is important with longer courses or abrupt discontinuation\n  after prolonged use. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review glucose, blood pressure, infection symptoms, GI bleed risk, steroid\n  dose/duration, taper plan, and discharge instructions.\n- Escalate severe hyperglycemia, infection concern, GI bleed symptoms, severe\n  psychiatric symptoms, or unclear taper.\n\n\n11. Nausea Medicines\n\nExamples:\nOndansetron, prochlorperazine, promethazine, metoclopramide.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Sleepiness, dizziness, constipation, dry mouth, headache, or fatigue may occur;\n  frequency varies by medicine. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Metoclopramide may cause drowsiness, fatigue, restlessness, or diarrhea.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Fainting, racing heartbeat, severe dizziness, or heart-rhythm symptoms are\n  less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Metoclopramide or dopamine-blocking antiemetics: restlessness, tremor,\n  stiffness, dystonia, tardive dyskinesia, or other unusual movements are less\n  common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Serotonin syndrome is less common but important when serotonergic combinations\n  are present. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review QT risk, sedation/fall risk, Parkinson disease, dopamine-blocking\n  combinations, serotonergic medicines, and duration limits for metoclopramide.\n- Escalate abnormal movements, severe sedation, QT/arrhythmia symptoms, or\n  suspected serotonin syndrome.\n\n\n12. Bowel Medicines\n\nExamples:\nSenna, polyethylene glycol, docusate, bisacodyl, lactulose.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Cramping, gas, bloating, loose stools, and diarrhea are common enough to\n  mention with bowel medicines. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Lactulose commonly causes gas, bloating, cramping, and diarrhea depending on\n  dose and bowel-movement goal. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Severe diarrhea, severe stomach pain, dehydration symptoms, or no bowel\n  movement when expected are less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label]\n- Significant electrolyte abnormalities can occur with severe or prolonged\n  diarrhea. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review bowel movement goals, stool frequency, dehydration risk, electrolytes\n  when clinically relevant, opioid use, and lactulose indication.\n- Escalate severe abdominal pain, persistent diarrhea, dehydration, or failure\n  to meet bowel goals in hepatic encephalopathy.\n\n\n13. Psychiatric, Sleep, and Anxiety Medicines\n\nExamples:\nSertraline, escitalopram, quetiapine, haloperidol, trazodone, melatonin,\nlorazepam.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Sleepiness, dizziness, dry mouth, nausea, constipation, headache, or fall risk\n  are common enough to mention for many of these medicines. [Source: DailyMed\n  FDA label]\n- SSRIs can cause GI upset, headache, sleep changes, sexual side effects, and\n  may take weeks for full mood benefit. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Antipsychotics can cause sedation, orthostasis, dry mouth, constipation, and\n  movement-related side effects. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Benzodiazepines can cause sedation, confusion, falls, dependence, and\n  respiratory depression risk, especially with opioids or other sedatives.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label; FDA opioid/benzodiazepine safety communication]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Severe sleepiness, confusion, slowed breathing, or falls are less common but\n  serious with sedating medicines. [Source: FDA opioid/benzodiazepine safety\n  communication; DailyMed FDA label]\n- New suicidal thoughts, severe mood changes, severe restlessness, stiffness,\n  fever, abnormal movements, or neuroleptic malignant syndrome symptoms are less\n  common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- QT-related symptoms are less common but important with selected agents.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review sedation, fall risk, QT risk, anticholinergic burden, serotonergic\n  combinations, withdrawal/dependence risk, and indication.\n- Escalate respiratory depression, severe confusion, abnormal movements, severe\n  agitation, suicidal thoughts, or arrhythmia symptoms.\n\n\n14. Seizure Medicines\n\nExamples:\nLevetiracetam, phenytoin, valproate, lacosamide, carbamazepine, oxcarbazepine,\nlamotrigine, topiramate, phenobarbital, gabapentin.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Sleepiness, dizziness, trouble walking, nausea, headache, fatigue, or mood\n  changes are common enough to mention for many seizure medicines. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n- Levetiracetam: sleepiness/fatigue, dizziness, and behavior or mood changes may\n  occur. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Phenytoin/fosphenytoin: dizziness, drowsiness, unsteady walking, slurred\n  speech, abnormal eye movements, nausea, and gum changes may occur; neurologic\n  symptoms can signal high levels. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Valproate: GI symptoms, sleepiness, dizziness, tremor, thrombocytopenia, and\n  weight changes may occur. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Lacosamide: dizziness, sleepiness, headache, nausea, double vision, and\n  unsteady walking may occur. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Carbamazepine/oxcarbazepine: dizziness, drowsiness, nausea, vomiting,\n  unsteady walking, low sodium, and rash may occur. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Lamotrigine: dizziness, headache, nausea, double vision, sleepiness,\n  coordination problems, and rash may occur. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Topiramate: sleepiness, dizziness, tingling, appetite/weight change, slowed\n  thinking, word-finding trouble, memory issues, and vision changes may occur.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Phenobarbital/gabapentin: sedation, dizziness, impaired coordination, and\n  fall risk may occur. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Severe rash, blistering rash, mouth sores, or skin peeling with lamotrigine,\n  carbamazepine, oxcarbazepine, or other seizure medicines is rare but serious.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Severe confusion, unsteady walking, slurred speech, abnormal eye movements, or\n  extreme sleepiness is less common but important and may suggest toxicity.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- New or worsening depression, suicidal thoughts, or major behavior changes are\n  less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Valproate: liver injury, pancreatitis, hyperammonemia, severe thrombocytopenia,\n  and serious birth-defect risk are less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed\n  FDA label]\n- Lacosamide: fainting, PR prolongation/heart rhythm changes, and serious\n  allergic reactions are less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Topiramate: acute eye pain/vision loss, metabolic acidosis, kidney stones,\n  overheating, and suicidal thoughts are less common but important. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n- Gabapentin or phenobarbital with opioids, benzodiazepines, alcohol, or other\n  sedatives: slowed breathing is less common but serious. [Source: DailyMed FDA\n  label; FDA opioid/CNS depressant safety communication; FDA\n  gabapentin/pregabalin safety communication]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review indication, renal/hepatic function, levels when applicable, albumin for\n  phenytoin interpretation, sodium for carbamazepine/oxcarbazepine, CBC/LFTs for\n  selected agents, pregnancy risk, sedation/falls, and discharge adherence plan.\n- Escalate serious rash, neurologic toxicity, suicidal thoughts, respiratory\n  depression, severe lab abnormalities, or uncontrolled seizures.\n\n\n15. Electrolytes and Supplements\n\nExamples:\nPotassium, magnesium, phosphate, iron, vitamin D, thiamine, folic acid.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Iron can cause constipation, dark stool, nausea, or stomach upset. These are\n  common enough to mention. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Magnesium can cause diarrhea and stomach upset. These are common enough to\n  mention. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Potassium can irritate the stomach, especially with oral tablets or liquid.\n  [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Severe stomach pain, severe diarrhea, vomiting, chest symptoms, severe\n  weakness, or trouble swallowing tablets is less common but important. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n- High or low potassium symptoms, severe weakness, palpitations, or arrhythmia\n  symptoms are less common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review renal function, electrolyte targets, route/formulation, GI tolerance,\n  and timing with interacting oral medications if discharge use is planned.\n- Escalate severe GI symptoms, trouble swallowing, severe weakness, palpitations,\n  or major electrolyte abnormalities.\n\n\n16. Alcohol Withdrawal or Substance-Use Medicines\n\nExamples:\nLorazepam, diazepam, phenobarbital, thiamine, folic acid, multivitamin,\nbuprenorphine, methadone, naltrexone.\n\nCommon or expected side effects:\n- Benzodiazepines and phenobarbital: sleepiness, dizziness, impaired\n  coordination, confusion, and fall risk are common enough to mention. [Source:\n  DailyMed FDA label]\n- Buprenorphine/methadone: sleepiness, dizziness, constipation, sweating,\n  nausea, and headache may occur. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Naltrexone: nausea, headache, dizziness, tiredness, and sleep changes may\n  occur. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nLess common but important warning signs:\n- Very slow breathing, extreme sleepiness, confusion, fainting, or severe\n  dizziness is less common but serious, especially with sedating combinations.\n  [Source: FDA opioid/benzodiazepine safety communication; DailyMed FDA label]\n- Methadone: chest palpitations, fainting, or QT-related symptoms are less\n  common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n- Naltrexone: liver injury symptoms or precipitated opioid withdrawal are less\n  common but important. [Source: DailyMed FDA label]\n\nMonitoring or escalation:\n- Review sedation, respiratory status, withdrawal scoring/protocol, QT risk for\n  methadone, liver function for naltrexone, opioid use history, and discharge\n  follow-up plan.\n- Escalate respiratory depression, oversedation, severe withdrawal, QT symptoms,\n  liver injury concern, or unclear outpatient continuation plan.\n\n\nSource Notes\n\nUse hospital-approved references for final verification. This file uses source\ntags beside side-effect information, but exact percentages should be verified\nfor the exact product and patient situation.\n\n- DailyMed Drug Labels\n  https://dailymed.nlm.nih.gov/dailymed/\n  Use for FDA-approved medication labels, adverse reaction frequency tables,\n  boxed warnings, warnings/precautions, contraindications, and interaction\n  information.\n\n- CDC: Antibiotic Use and Side Effects\n  https://www.cdc.gov/antibiotic-use/\n  Use for patient-friendly antibiotic side-effect counseling.\n\n- CDC: C. diff\n  https://www.cdc.gov/c-diff/\n  Use for antibiotic-associated severe diarrhea and C. diff counseling.\n\n- FDA: Opioid Pain Medicines Safety Information\n  https://www.fda.gov/drugs/information-drug-class/opioid-medications\n  Use for opioid safety, overdose, slowed breathing, dependence, and safe-use\n  counseling.\n\n- FDA: Opioids with Benzodiazepines or Other CNS Depressants\n  https://www.fda.gov/drugs/drug-safety-and-availability/fda-drug-safety-communication-fda-warns-about-serious-risks-and-death-when-combining-opioid\n  Use for serious sedation and breathing-risk counseling when opioids are\n  combined with benzodiazepines, alcohol, sleep medicines, or other CNS\n  depressants.\n\n- FDA: Gabapentin/Pregabalin and Serious Breathing Problems\n  https://www.fda.gov/drugs/drug-safety-and-availability/fda-warns-about-serious-breathing-problems-seizure-and-nerve-pain-medicines-gabapentin\n  Use for breathing-risk counseling when gabapentin or pregabalin is combined\n  with opioids or other CNS depressants, or when patients have respiratory risk\n  factors.\n\n- MedlinePlus: Hypoglycemia\n  https://medlineplus.gov/hypoglycemia.html\n  Use for patient-friendly low blood sugar symptoms.\n\n- MedlinePlus: Prednisone\n  https://medlineplus.gov/druginfo/meds/a601102.html\n  Use for patient-friendly steroid counseling.\n"};